        <span class="opacity-50">·</span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="font-heading text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl leading-tight">Hardwood vs Luxury Vinyl Plank (LVP): Which Is Right for Your Home?</h1>
      <p class="mt-4 text-brand-ink/70 text-sm">Published May 2026 · By Joey Jamail</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article class="container mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 pb-16 max-w-3xl text-brand-ink/90 leading-relaxed text-[1.0625rem]">

    <p>Walk into any Houston flooring showroom and you'll be offered both. The salesperson will say LVP is "just as good as hardwood, cheaper, waterproof, kid-proof, dog-proof." Some of that's true. Most of it isn't. Here's the honest comparison.</p>

    <p class="mt-4">Short version: <strong>LVP is fine for budget-constrained projects, rentals, basements, and high-water-risk areas. Real hardwood is the right choice for almost everything else — better looking, more durable over decades, and adds significant resale value.</strong></p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Cost</h2>
    <p>In Houston in 2026, installed pricing roughly:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>LVP (luxury vinyl plank):</strong> $7–$13/sq ft installed</li>
      <li><strong>Engineered hardwood (mid-tier):</strong> $15–$20/sq ft installed</li>
      <li><strong>Engineered hardwood (premium European):</strong> $20–$28/sq ft installed</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3">LVP wins on upfront cost by a wide margin — half to two-thirds the price.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">But that's not the whole cost picture. Hardwood lasts 30–80 years and can be refinished. LVP lasts 5–15 years and can't be refinished — once worn, it's replaced. Over 20 years, the lifetime cost is often <em>lower</em> with hardwood.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Looks (close up vs at 6 feet)</h2>
    <p>At 6 feet, mid-grade LVP looks convincingly like hardwood. The print quality is impressive — visible grain, knots, color variation. From across the room, it's hard to tell.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">At 2 feet, the illusion breaks. The print is too perfect — patterns repeat. The texture is plastic-feeling. Edges are uniform. Real wood has natural variation; LVP has manufactured "natural variation" that reads as fake on close inspection.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In photography (real estate listings, social media), LVP looks great. In person, premium hardwood is unmistakably better.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Durability</h2>
    <p>This is where the LVP marketing exaggerates. The truth:</p>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li><strong>LVP scratch resistance:</strong> Better than hardwood at first. But the wear layer is finite — once scratched through, the print is exposed and looks awful. Cannot be repaired.</li>
      <li><strong>Hardwood scratch resistance:</strong> Worse at first. But scratches in real hardwood can be sanded out, oiled, or refinished. The floor can be restored.</li>
      <li><strong>LVP under heavy loads:</strong> Soft. Heavy furniture can permanently dent. Cast-iron skillet drops leave permanent marks.</li>
      <li><strong>Hardwood under heavy loads:</strong> Hard. Dents are possible but rare.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Over 5–10 years</strong>, LVP visibly degrades. Edges curl, color fades unevenly under sunlight, the print wears in high-traffic areas. <strong>Over 5–10 years</strong>, well-installed hardwood looks essentially the same as the day it was installed.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Water resistance</h2>
    <p>LVP wins this round, cleanly. LVP is fully waterproof — no warping from spills, no buckling from leaks. For basements, bathrooms, mudrooms, and very flood-prone areas, LVP is the right call.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Engineered hardwood is more water-resistant than solid hardwood but not waterproof. Standing water for hours can cause swelling and warping.</p>
    <p class="mt-3"><strong>Houston-specific:</strong> If your home flooded in Harvey or you live in a known flood zone, LVP downstairs is reasonable. For most Houston homes — even with kids, dogs, and the occasional spill — engineered hardwood handles real life fine.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Resale value</h2>
    <p>Real estate agents in Houston are nearly unanimous: <strong>real hardwood adds meaningfully more resale value than LVP</strong>, especially in homes priced over $400K.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Buyers in the $500K+ Houston market expect real hardwood. LVP in this segment reads as "the previous owner cheaped out" even when the LVP itself looks fine. We've seen homes appraise $20K–$50K higher specifically because of premium hardwood specification.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">In the under-$300K market, LVP doesn't hurt resale much. Above $400K, hardwood pays for itself.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">Feel underfoot</h2>
    <p>Hardwood feels warm, solid, slightly soft. It has the right amount of give and grip. It muffles sound naturally.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">LVP feels colder (especially over slab), slightly hollow, more "plastic." It echoes more. Walking on it sounds different than walking on wood.</p>
    <p class="mt-3">Sounds small. It's actually a big difference once you live with it.</p>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">When LVP is the right choice</h2>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Budget under $10/sq ft installed</li>
      <li>Basement or below-grade</li>
      <li>Known flood-risk area</li>
      <li>Rental property where wear-and-tear is the concern</li>
      <li>Short ownership horizon (selling within 2–3 years)</li>
      <li>Heavy pet household with very large or active dogs</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">When hardwood is the right choice</h2>
    <ul class="mt-3 space-y-2 list-disc pl-6">
      <li>Forever-home renovations</li>
      <li>Homes over $400K</li>
      <li>Above-grade slab (most Houston homes)</li>
      <li>Owners who care how the floor looks at year 10</li>
      <li>Properties where resale matters</li>
      <li>Design-conscious households</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl sm:text-3xl text-brand-coal mt-10 mb-4">The honest bottom line</h2>
    <p>If you can afford premium hardwood, it's almost always the better choice. If your budget caps at $10/sq ft installed, mid-grade LVP is honest, durable enough, and looks fine in photographs. Just don't pay LVP money expecting hardwood quality — it's a different product.</p>

  </article>

